%I A046160 #36 Mar 28 2026 23:19:17
%S A046160 2,5,6,9,11,14,15,18,21,23,27,29,30,33,38,39,41,45,50,51,54,59,63,65,
%T A046160 66,69,75,77,78,81,83,86,93,95,99,102,105,110,111,113,114,119,123,126,
%U A046160 129,131,135,141,146,149,150,153,158,159,165,171,173,174,177,183
%N A046160 Bends of spheres in Soddy's bowl of integers which are tangent to the unit sphere and a single 2-sphere.
%C A046160 From _Martin Fuller_, Mar 28 2026: (Start)
%C A046160 Apart from the first term, the definition corresponds to Fig 2 in Soddy's paper, and to this text opposite the figure: "successive rings I, 3 ;  II, 6, 5 ;  III, 11, 9, 9 ;  IV, 18, 15, 14, 15 ;  V, 27, 23, 21, 21, 23 ;  VI, 38, 33, 30, 29, 30, 33 and so on."
%C A046160 The list of all bends in the bowl is given by A045506. The smallest number in A045506 not in A046159 or A046160 is 8; this sphere is not shown in Fig 2 but would be tangent to (5,3,3,-1), outside the displayed spheres, each side of the equator.
%C A046160 Conjecture: the list of bends of all spheres not in the plane is A049636 "Congruent to 0 or 2 mod 3, but not equal to 0 or 3." (End)
%H A046160 Frederick Soddy, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/139077a0">The Bowl of Integers and the Hexlet</a>, Nature 139, 77-79, 1937 [<a href="https://scispace.com/pdf/the-bowl-of-integers-and-the-hexlet-2g1v1j2x4s.pdf">Accessible copy</a>]
%H A046160 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/BowlofIntegers.html">Bowl of Integers.</a>
%e A046160 a(1) = 2 is the bend of the two "initial" spheres of radius 1/2, centered in (0, 0, +- 0.5), touching each other at the origin, and the unit sphere in (0, 0, +-1). Next there are six spheres of radius 1/3, centered in the plane, each of which touches its two neighbor spheres with bend 3, and also the two spheres of bend 2, and also the outer sphere of bend -1. Since their center is on the plane, their bend is not listed here.
%e A046160 a(2) = 5 is the bend of the two times six spheres that can be filled in between the spheres of bend 2 and the above mentioned spheres of bend 3, six above and six below the plane z=0. Since their center is not in the plane, their bend is again listed here.
%o A046160 (PARI) a(limit)={
%o A046160   my(L = List([[5,3,2,-1]]), R = List(2));
%o A046160   while(1,
%o A046160     if(#R >= limit, return(Vec(R)));
%o A046160     listsort(~L);
%o A046160     my(k = L[1]);
%o A046160     listpop(~L, 1);
%o A046160     if(k[1] > R[#R], listput(~R, k[1]));
%o A046160     my(s = vecsum(k), ss = norml2(k));
%o A046160     my(kn = (sqrtint((#k-1)*(s^2 - (#k-2)*ss)) + s) / (#k-2));
%o A046160     if(kn > k[1], listput(~L, [kn, k[2], k[3], k[4]]));
%o A046160     if(kn >= k[1] && kn > k[2], listput(~L, [kn, k[1], k[3], k[4]]));
%o A046160   );
%o A046160 }; \\ _Martin Fuller_, Mar 28 2026
%Y A046160 Cf. A046159 (bends of spheres centered on the plane).
%Y A046160 Cf. A045506 (list of all bends: -1, 2, 3, 5, ...).
%K A046160 nonn,nice,changed
%O A046160 1,1
%A A046160 _Eric W. Weisstein_
%E A046160 Description revised, a(12)=29 inserted and a(15) onward from _Martin Fuller_, Mar 28 2026
